 sometimes be viable. He concludes that these trends in the international setting call for major shifts in our understanding of what constitutes stable governance-proposing that we adopt a fluid "emergent actor" approach. And he calls for significant deviation from standard policy responses to the opportunities and dangers posed by nontraditional sources of national authority.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aNon-state actors (International relations) 0aPolitical stability. 0aSecurity, International. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Security (National & International).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080478649240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804786492423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804786492.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles